eas of research as they shed light on well-known writers. This volume situates nineteenth-century Latino intellectuals and writers within crucial national, hemispheric, and regional debates. The Latino Nineteenth Century offers a long-overdue corrective to the Anglophone and nation-based emphasis of American literary history. Contributors track Latino/a lives and writing through routes that span Philadelphia to San Francisco and roots that extend deeply into Mexico, the Caribbean, Central and South Americas, and Spain. Readers will find in the rich heterogeneity of texts and authors discussed fertile ground for discussion and will discover the depth, diversity, and long-standing presence of Latinos/as and their literature in the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmerican literaturexHispanic American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aHispanic American literature (Spanish)xHistory and criticism. 0aHispanic AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aLatin American literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aSpanish American literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh1 aAlemán, Jesse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlemán, Jesse, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAranda, José, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer, Ralph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBramen, Carrie Tirado, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoronado, Raúl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutler, John Alba, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGruesz, Kir